body:
In `Discovered HardwareMonitor.Timer_Elapsed`

While investigating NullReferenceException that happens sometimes inside `computer.Open()`, discovered that `Timer_Elapsed` was called again, before first call finished.

I examined this by giving each call a new "ID". And tracking what the latest ID started was, in the middle and at end of a given method run.

Got output like this:
```cs
HardwareMonitor EXCEPTION #6 seeing #8
HardwareMonitor BEFORE #9 seeing #9
HardwareMonitor AFTER #7 seeing #9
HardwareMonitor BEFORE #10 seeing #10
HardwareMonitor BEFORE #11 seeing #11
HardwareMonitor AFTER #11 seeing #11
```

Explanation:  
```
* Timer_Elapsed run #6 got an exception, while trying to run at the same time as run #8.
* By the time run #7 finished, run #9 had started.
```

Fix:  
Use a boolean flag to know when this code is already running.  
If it is, skip this run.  
```cs
private static long _iPrevCall;
private static bool _isBusy;
private void Timer_Elapsed(object? sender, System.Timers.ElapsedEventArgs e)
{
	if (_isBusy)
	{
		// Skip this time.
		Debug.WriteLine($"HardwareMonitor SKIPPED when called again during #{_iPrevCall}");
		return;
	}
	
	_isBusy = true;
	_iPrevCall++;
	var iCall = _iPrevCall;
	try
	{
		Debug.WriteLine($"HardwareMonitor BEFORE #{iCall}");
... 	// ... YOUR CODE HERE ...
		Debug.WriteLine($"HardwareMonitor AFTER #{iCall}");
	}
	catch (Exception ex)
	{
		Debug.WriteLine(ex.ToString());
		Debug.WriteLine($"HardwareMonitor EXCEPTION #{iCall}");
		return;
	}
	finally
	{
		_isBusy = false;
	}
}
```

Now output is similar to this:
```cs
HardwareMonitor BEFORE #2
HardwareMonitor SKIPPED when called again during #2
HardwareMonitor SKIPPED when called again during #2
HardwareMonitor AFTER #2
HardwareMonitor BEFORE #3
HardwareMonitor SKIPPED when called again during #3
HardwareMonitor SKIPPED when called again during #3
HardwareMonitor AFTER #3
```

OBSERVE: No Exceptions. Those were caused by attempting to use multiple `LibreHardwareMonitor.Hardware.Computer`s at same time.  
 (I did see one System.Management.Exception; don't know if this code or other code.)

This also should be better performance than running multiple at same time.  
(Likely not significant performance for this code, but if app has other code with similar re-entrancy, could become significant.)
